00:10:41,558 --> 00:10:43,030
deploy this labeling job.

243
00:10:43,030 --> 00:10:47,200
We could also do a
manual data setup, where

244
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:49,030
we specify the input
data set location,

245
00:10:49,030 --> 00:10:51,130
output data set
location, basically,

246
00:10:51,130 --> 00:10:53,920
where we want the labels to go.

247
00:10:53,920 --> 00:10:56,170
Actually, I think we might
have to specify that still.

248
00:10:56,170 --> 00:10:57,670
Yeah, we still have
to specify that.

249
00:10:57,670 --> 00:11:00,710
But basically, it'll remove
some of the automated steps that

250
00:11:00,710 --> 00:11:02,150
are going to happen.

251
00:11:02,150 --> 00:11:04,920
So we're going to do the
automated setup, though.

252
00:11:04,920 --> 00:11:08,250
And so we'll browse S3 for
a location of our data sets.

253
00:11:08,250 --> 00:11:10,610
So we'll do data3600demo.

254
00:11:10,610 --> 00:11:13,910
And then where did I go here?

255
00:11:13,910 --> 00:11:17,402
ground-truth-demo, and Images.

256
00:11:17,402 --> 00:11:18,860
So actually, let's
go back in here.

257
00:11:18,860 --> 00:11:21,350
We just need to click Images.

258
00:11:21,350 --> 00:11:24,060
I think we want to
do it at that level.

259
00:11:24,060 --> 00:11:25,270
Yeah.

260
00:11:25,270 --> 00:11:26,420
So let's select that.

261
00:11:26,420 --> 00:11:29,540
And so that's going to be
the input data set location.

262
00:11:29,540 --> 00:11:31,720
And then we want to have
the output labels go

263
00:11:31,720 --> 00:11:33,058
to a different location.

264
00:11:33,058 --> 00:11:34,600
And for that matter,
let me make sure

265
00:11:34,600 --> 00:11:36,020
that I don't have something.

266
00:11:36,020 --> 00:11:36,740
Actually, it doesn't matter.

267
00:11:36,740 --> 00:11:37,573
It's not a big deal.

268
00:11:37,573 --> 00:11:39,050
We're not going
to run it anyways.

269
00:11:39,050 --> 00:11:42,380
But we're going to do
output data set location.

270
00:11:42,380 --> 00:11:44,270
And so I'm just copying
and pasting this,

271
00:11:44,270 --> 00:11:48,537
but I'm going to change
this to say labeled-data2.

272
00:11:48,537 --> 00:11:50,870
That's where I'm going to
tell it to go to-- the bucket.

273
00:11:50,870 --> 00:11:53,440
I'm going to tell it to go to

274
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:55,510
The data type here,
as we said, there

275
00:11:55,510 --> 00:11:57,560
are images, so we can
just tell it that.

276
00:11:57,560 --> 00:12:02,620
But you see here, it has
automated data setup features

277
00:12:02,620 --> 00:12:05,180
for text, video,
and video frames.

278
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:07,870
So you can do any of those.

279
00:12:07,870 --> 00:12:11,180
And then as far as the role
that we need, let me see,

280
00:12:11,180 --> 00:12:14,260
I think we need to create
a new role for this.

281
00:12:14,260 --> 00:12:16,210
Let's do Create a New Role.

282
00:12:16,210 --> 00:12:19,480
And we're just saying, it can
have access to any S3 bucket

283
00:12:19,480 --> 00:12:21,825
because we're letting it set
it up anywhere it needs to.

284
00:12:24,450 --> 00:12:25,290
OK.

285
00:12:25,290 --> 00:12:26,620
And Then now we can--

286
00:12:26,620 --> 00:12:29,260
I don't think we need
anything here just yet.

287
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:29,760
Yeah.

288
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:34,210
So this is just if you want
to not label all the images.

289
00:12:34,210 --> 00:12:36,810
You want to label a random
sample or a specific subsample

290
00:12:36,810 --> 00:12:37,450
of it.

291
00:12:37,450 --> 00:12:40,680
For now, we're saying, we want
everything labeled, if possible.

292
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:42,240
So we'll do Complete Data Setup.

293
00:12:42,240 --> 00:12:44,010
And you'll see, it actually
has a loading step here,

294
00:12:44,010 --> 00:12:46,590
because what's happening now
is it's going in and creating

295
00:12:46,590 --> 00:12:48,270
that manifest file.

296
00:12:48,270 --> 00:12:53,400
So if I go to S3 really
quick, let me open up S3.

297
00:12:53,400 --> 00:12:54,450
Let's go here.

298
00:12:54,450 --> 00:12:54,950
S3.

299
00:12:57,630 --> 00:13:02,710
And if we go into data3600demo,
ground-truth-demo, Images,

300
00:13:02,710 --> 00:13:05,710
you'll see that,
today's November 27,

301
00:13:05,710 --> 00:13:08,293
it just created this
manifest file here.

302
00:13:08,293 --> 00:13:10,710
And so again, this manifest
file just tells it information

303
00:13:10,710 --> 00:13:12,877
or it contains this information
about the files that

304
00:13:12,877 --> 00:13:15,920
are in this folder.

305
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:18,140
So coming back here
then, we can now

306
00:13:18,140 --> 00:13:21,830
come down to some more
information about the task type.

307
00:13:21,830 --> 00:13:25,680
So in here, we obviously
are doing image.

308
00:13:25,680 --> 00:13:27,150
We already told it that.

309
00:13:27,150 --> 00:13:29,490
But now, you can select
what specific task.

310
00:13:29,490 --> 00:13:31,430
So this will be an
image classification

311
00:13:31,430 --> 00:13:32,610
task with a single label.

312
00:13:32,610 --> 00:13:34,110
So we can leave
this one checked.

313
00:13:34,110 --> 00:13:35,690
But it's the
equivalent of saying,

314
00:13:35,690 --> 00:13:38,750
what is the thing in this image?

315
00:13:38,750 --> 00:13:42,740
Though, arguably, this can
be a little bit fuzzy because

316
00:13:42,740 --> 00:13:44,975
for example, even
in this image, yes,

317
00:13:44,975 --> 00:13:47,100
maybe if the two choices
were basketball or soccer,

318
00:13:47,100 --> 00:13:48,570
the label is basketball.

319
00:13:48,570 --> 00:13:51,590
But be mindful that when we
train the machine learning

320
00:13:51,590 --> 00:13:55,110
model, it doesn't know what part
of this image is basketball.

321
00:13:55,110 --> 00:13:57,770
So if maybe all of our
examples of basketball

322
00:13:57,770 --> 00:14:01,850
were images taken in a city,
and all of our images of soccer

323
00:14:01,850 --> 00:14:04,850
were images taken in a
rural area or an area

324
00:14:04,850 --> 00:14:06,680
that is away from
buildings, it might

325
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:08,420
learn to just
associate basketball

326
00:14:08,420 --> 00:14:12,950
with buildings and soccer
with blue open skies.

327
00:14:12,950 --> 00:14:15,060
That is obviously not
what we want it to learn.

328
00:14:15,060 --> 00:14:18,610
So single label classification
can have that outcome

329
00:14:18,610 --> 00:14:21,660
if you don't have a good
representative data set.

330
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:24,070
For now, we'll take this
as gospel and go with it,

331
00:14:24,070 --> 00:14:27,330
but be mindful of that issue.

332
00:14:27,330 --> 00:14:29,220
Moving on to multilabel
classification.

333
00:14:29,220 --> 00:14:30,360
And we'll just talk
about what each of these

334
00:14:30,360 --> 00:14:33,340
are really quickly here, so you
know what they're talking about.

335
00:14:33,340 --> 00:14:35,820
Multilabel classification
is arguably a bit more

336
00:14:35,820 --> 00:14:39,150
appropriate of a task, though,
it's more time-consuming,

337
00:14:39,150 --> 00:14:40,810
because multilabel
classification says,

338
00:14:40,810 --> 00:14:41,970
well, here's a
long list of things

339
00:14:41,970 --> 00:14:43,150
that could be in the image.

340
00:14:43,150 --> 00:14:45,760
Just check what all the
things are in the image.

341
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:48,030
Now, it still might be the
case that you don't include

342
00:14:48,030 --> 00:14:49,420
the right category
because maybe, again,

343
00:14:49,420 --> 00:14:51,340
you don't include
building as an option.

344
00:14:51,340 --> 00:14:53,280
And so therefore, that
doesn't get picked up

345
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:55,060
as something that
could be in the image.

346
00:14:55,060 --> 00:14:59,370
But it's at least a little bit
more verbose or a little bit

347
00:14:59,370 --> 00:15:02,280
more detailed of a task.

348
00:15:02,280 --> 00:15:08,160
But again, downside here
is that we're not only

349
00:15:08,160 --> 00:15:13,500
going to be susceptible to
any classes or any categories

350
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:15,570
that we didn't
include, but also, it's

351
00:15:15,570 --> 00:15:17,520
going to be more time-consuming.

352
00:15:17,520 --> 00:15:19,320
And as we go down
this list, everything

353
00:15:19,320 --> 00:15:22,180
is basically getting more
and more time-consuming,

354
00:15:22,180 --> 00:15:24,330
which means it's
going to cost us more

355
00:15:24,330 --> 00:15:27,150
to get the labels for this.

356
00:15:27,150 --> 00:15:29,200
OK, that's image
classification multilabel.

357
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:31,290
Next step down is
bounding boxes.

358
00:15:31,290 --> 00:15:34,740
So this is now saying, OK,
can you identify not only

359
00:15:34,740 --> 00:15:39,510
potentially, what the object is,
but also draw a box around it?

360
00:15:39,510 --> 00:15:41,010
And drawing this
box around it, now,

361
00:15:41,010 --> 00:15:43,270
lets me do something
really much more valuable.

362
00:15:43,270 --> 00:15:45,677
So again, thinking about the
self-driving car scenario.

363
00:15:45,677 --> 00:15:48,010
I not only need to know that
there's a car in the image,

364
00:15:48,010 --> 00:15:50,040
I need to know where
that car is in the image

365
00:15:50,040 --> 00:15:52,032
and how much of the
frame it's taking up.

366
00:15:52,032 --> 00:15:53,740
Because if it's taking
up a lot of space,

367
00:15:53,740 --> 00:15:56,475
that means the car is very close
to me versus if it's taking up

368
00:15:56,475 --> 00:15:58,350
a small amount of space,
that car is very far

369
00:15:58,350 --> 00:15:59,500
and everything's OK.

370
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:02,100
So the bounding box can
arguably be much more important

371
00:16:02,100 --> 00:16:04,003
than anything else.

372
00:16:04,003 --> 00:16:05,920
So either way, that's
the next one up, though.

373
00:16:05,920 --> 00:16:08,240
Again, it does take
more time to label.

374
00:16:08,240 --> 00:16:11,280
And then finally, the most
time-consuming labeling task

375
00:16:11,280 --> 00:16:12,870
is semantic segmentation.

376
00:16:12,870 --> 00:16:15,210
As you can see in this
image, that's not only

377
00:16:15,210 --> 00:16:17,740
just identifying
what the object is,

378
00:16:17,740 --> 00:16:21,210
but also outlining
the exact shape of it.

379
00:16:21,210 --> 00:16:22,860
So I know exactly
which pixels are

380
00:16:22,860 --> 00:16:28,320
associated with car versus
person or purse versus phone.

381
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:30,630
Now, it has another
byproduct, and this same issue

382
00:16:30,630 --> 00:16:32,820
happens with bounding
box as well too, is that,

383
00:16:32,820 --> 00:16:35,170
again, if I don't include
a category for buildings,

384
00:16:35,170 --> 00:16:37,620
it just gets lumped into
the background class.

385
00:16:37,620 --> 00:16:40,050
And everything that's not one
of the known labels or one

386
00:16:40,050 --> 00:16:42,240
of the provided
choices for a label

387
00:16:42,240 --> 00:16:45,540
is just lumped in as
the background class.

388
00:16:45,540 --> 00:16:51,012
Now, the reality of this is from
a practical machine learning

389
00:16:51,012 --> 00:16:52,470
standpoint, what
we're really doing

390
00:16:52,470 --> 00:16:55,720
is predicting what every
pixel is in this image.

391
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:57,870
And then we'll connect
contiguous regions

392
00:16:57,870 --> 00:17:01,780
into an object, let's say.

393
00:17:01,780 --> 00:17:05,263
So we would go down this
image, one pixel at a time.

394
00:17:05,263 --> 00:17:07,180
And as we're coming
through here, all of these

395
00:17:07,180 --> 00:17:08,089
are background.

396
00:17:08,089 --> 00:17:11,329
But as we start to
hit this woman's hair,

397
00:17:11,329 --> 00:17:14,450
we would say, OK, this pixel
is associated with person.

398
00:17:14,450 --> 00:17:15,950
And so we're going
to color it pink.

399
00:17:15,950 --> 00:17:17,470
We're just going to
identify this as person.

400
00:17:17,470 --> 00:17:18,890
And we're just going to
keep going through here,

401
00:17:18,890 --> 00:17:21,920
identifying each pixel, and then
connecting contiguous regions.

402
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:24,829
Again, this is super, super
time-consuming to label.

403
00:17:24,829 --> 00:17:27,145
So it's really hard to get
large data sets with this,

404
00:17:27,145 --> 00:17:29,270
though, these are the most
valuable, because again,

405
00:17:29,270 --> 00:17:31,450
if I have semantic
segmentation, I

406
00:17:31,450 --> 00:17:33,327
can reconstruct all
of these labels.

407
00:17:33,327 --> 00:17:34,910
I could know what
the bounding box is.

408
00:17:34,910 --> 00:17:36,350
I can know what
the multi-label is.

409
00:17:36,350 --> 00:17:38,600
I could even potentially cut
it down to a single label

410
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:40,630
if there's only one
object in the image.

411
00:17:40,630 --> 00:17:42,430
Semantic segmentation
is also something

412
00:17:42,430 --> 00:17:45,680
that you guys have probably
used pretty frequently.

413
00:17:45,680 --> 00:17:48,050
If you have a portrait
mode on your phone,

414
00:17:48,050 --> 00:17:53,080
like on your cell phone to take
images with, where it blurs out

415
00:17:53,080 --> 00:17:56,240
the background to create this
kind of dramatic photography,

416
00:17:56,240 --> 00:18:00,320
nice bokeh effect, that
is semantic segmentation.

417
00:18:00,320 --> 00:18:01,900
It's predicting
whether each pixel

418
00:18:01,900 --> 00:18:03,453
is foreground or background.

419
00:18:03,453 --> 00:18:05,120
Anything foreground,
it leaves in focus.

420
00:18:05,120 --> 00:18:07,340
Anything background,
it artificially blurs,

421
00:18:07,340 --> 00:18:09,490
creating that depth
of field effect.

422
00:18:09,490 --> 00:18:12,440
So again, all of these are
really practical things,

423
00:18:12,440 --> 00:18:15,700
but they increase in time
that it takes to get them.

424
00:18:15,700 --> 00:18:17,680
The one last one here
that we can choose from

425
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:19,250
is label verification.

426
00:18:19,250 --> 00:18:21,790
Now, label verification
is just saying, OK, well,

427
00:18:21,790 --> 00:18:23,098
what if we already have labels?

428
00:18:23,098 --> 00:18:24,640
What if somebody
went through and did

429
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:26,390
one of these labeling tasks.

430
00:18:26,390 --> 00:18:28,060
Can I now have another
person go through

431
00:18:28,060 --> 00:18:30,400
and just verify whether
that's true or not?

432
00:18:30,400 --> 00:18:33,670
Arguably, if I had multiple
people go through this over

433
00:18:33,670 --> 00:18:36,640
and over and verify it,
first off, verifying labels

434
00:18:36,640 --> 00:18:40,097
is much faster than
making new labels.

435
00:18:40,097 --> 00:18:42,680
For example, with the semantic
segmentation, I could just say,

436
00:18:42,680 --> 00:18:46,220
well, is this object correctly
outlined as car, yes or no?

437
00:18:46,220 --> 00:18:48,490
And if it's yes or if the
vast majority of people

438
00:18:48,490 --> 00:18:51,170
say yes that do the
label verification task,

439
00:18:51,170 --> 00:18:52,760
then I can just
accept that as, OK,

440
00:18:52,760 --> 00:18:54,050
that's probably ground truth.

441
00:18:54,050 --> 00:18:55,600
That's an OK label.

442
00:18:55,600 --> 00:18:57,520
And so that is another
really useful step

443
00:18:57,520 --> 00:19:01,240
that can be very valuable.

444
00:19:01,240 --> 00:19:02,980
So again, long winded
way to say, let's

445
00:19:02,980 --> 00:19:06,650
stick with image classification
with a single label for now.

446
00:19:06,650 --> 00:19:09,363
And then once we've done
that, we'll just click Next.

447
00:19:09,363 --> 00:19:12,030
And everything up to this point,
if you've been following along,

448
00:19:12,030 --> 00:19:12,830
is not charging us.

449
00:19:12,830 --> 00:19:14,622
Again, I'll tell you
once you actually have

450
00:19:14,622 --> 00:19:16,560
to worry about the charging.

451
00:19:16,560 --> 00:19:18,450
So now, we can scroll
back up to the top

452
00:19:18,450 --> 00:19:20,760
here once we've gotten
to the next screen.

453
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:22,980
And now is actually
the choice of how

454
00:19:22,980 --> 00:19:24,660
we go about doing the labeling.

455
00:19:24,660 --> 00:19:26,390
So if we start with private.

456
00:19:26,390 --> 00:19:28,560
Private is probably
the simplest one

457
00:19:28,560 --> 00:19:30,300
to think about that's
saying, Hey, I'm

458
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:32,120
going to go ahead and
do the labeling here.

459
00:19:32,120 --> 00:19:33,910
Maybe my team is going
to do the labeling.

460
00:19:33,910 --> 00:19:35,670
So just set up all
the architecture

461
00:19:35,670 --> 00:19:38,790
for us to go in here and
actually do the task.

462
00:19:38,790 --> 00:19:41,700
That is useful if you have a
team that can do the labeling

463
00:19:41,700 --> 00:19:44,370
or maybe if you have a very
specialized or sensitive task

464
00:19:44,370 --> 00:19:47,940
where you need that data to
stay within your organization.

465
00:19:47,940 --> 00:19:53,490
But again, it's going to require
the most resources on your end.

466
00:19:53,490 --> 00:19:55,230
Now, there's also,
though, and we're not

467
00:19:55,230 --> 00:19:56,980
going to really talk
about vendor-managed,

468
00:19:56,980 --> 00:19:59,220
this is a separate
thing that, again,

469
00:19:59,220 --> 00:20:00,970
if you need vendor-managed,
you'll use it.

470
00:20:00,970 --> 00:20:02,410
I mean, obviously, you can
read what it does here,

471
00:20:02,410 --> 00:20:04,080
curated list of
third party vendors

472
00:20:04,080 --> 00:20:07,240
that specialize in providing
data labeling services.

473
00:20:07,240 --> 00:20:12,070
But arguably, more useful
is Amazon's Mechanical Turk.

474
00:20:12,070 --> 00:20:15,600
This is a special case of the
vendor-managed in that this

475
00:20:15,600 --> 00:20:17,900
is built into Amazon.

476
00:20:17,900 --> 00:20:20,410
And so what Mechanical Turk
does, and actually, we actually

477
00:20:20,410 --> 00:20:22,493
talked about this in one
of the previous lectures,

478
00:20:22,493 --> 00:20:27,130
but as a refresher, at least,
it is effectively gig work.

479
00:20:27,130 --> 00:20:28,900
It's a gig economy,
the same as you

480
00:20:28,900 --> 00:20:31,010
have with an Uber or
something like that,

481
00:20:31,010 --> 00:20:32,870
except rather than them
driving you around,

482
00:20:32,870 --> 00:20:33,980
it's a bunch of people.

483
00:20:33,980 --> 00:20:36,850
You can see here, they have over
500,000 independent contractors

484
00:20:36,850 --> 00:20:41,380
worldwide that are just waiting
and ready to do these types

485
00:20:41,380 --> 00:20:43,520
of tasks or these
low level tasks.

486
00:20:43,520 --> 00:20:45,820
This is used very
often in research

487
00:20:45,820 --> 00:20:49,210
because it's an easy
way to get a lot of data

488
00:20:49,210 --> 00:20:52,520
created from humans without
having to recruit new humans.

489
00:20:52,520 --> 00:20:56,980
You just pay them per task,
and you can access that.

490
00:20:56,980 --> 00:21:01,780
So that's the one I used to
do this demo in this class.

491
00:21:01,780 --> 00:21:04,000
So now, once we've
selected that, you can see,

492
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:07,090
we can first specify
how long before--

493
00:21:07,090 --> 00:21:09,890
or how much time can a worker
spend on a single task.

494
00:21:09,890 --> 00:21:12,947
This is not saying that we
are necessarily paying them

495
00:21:12,947 --> 00:21:15,530
for the whole five minutes they
could potentially spend there,

496
00:21:15,530 --> 00:21:16,600
but maybe it's
something where we

497
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:19,390
don't want them to have infinite
amount of time researching it.

498
00:21:19,390 --> 00:21:20,890
Or maybe it's
something where I need

499
00:21:20,890 --> 00:21:23,840
them to make really quick
responses to simulate something.

500
00:21:23,840 --> 00:21:26,660
And so I can constrain
the task time out here.

501
00:21:26,660 --> 00:21:30,072
And similarly, I can specify
the expiration time, so

502
00:21:30,072 --> 00:21:32,530
the amount of time that a task
remains available to workers

503
00:21:32,530 --> 00:21:33,970
before expiring.

504
00:21:33,970 --> 00:21:37,120
So both of these are
intertwined in that sense.

505
00:21:37,120 --> 00:21:40,540
But more important here
is this price per task.

506
00:21:40,540 --> 00:21:42,820
This price per task is
how much you're actually

507
00:21:42,820 --> 00:21:46,930
going to be paying
the Mechanical Turk

508
00:21:46,930 --> 00:21:49,340
worker to do the task.

509
00:21:49,340 --> 00:21:52,640
So in our case, a task would
be labeling a single image.

510
00:21:52,640 --> 00:21:55,640
So looking at one
of our images here,

511
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:57,460
if we just click
into one of them.

512
00:21:57,460 --> 00:22:01,540
So asking the user to say,
what is in this image?

513
00:22:01,540 --> 00:22:04,630
Is it car, motorcycle,
plane, boat?

514
00:22:04,630 --> 00:22:07,420
That task there is one task.

515
00:22:07,420 --> 00:22:10,580
And how much do you want to pay
for that is listed right here.

516
00:22:10,580 --> 00:22:12,700
So you can see,
they have basically

517
00:22:12,700 --> 00:22:15,705
recommended guidelines based off
of the complexity of the task.

518
00:22:15,705 --> 00:22:17,830
So this would definitely
fall into a low complexity

519
00:22:17,830 --> 00:22:19,953
task, where with
five or six labels,

520
00:22:19,953 --> 00:22:21,620
it's going to be
relatively quick to do,

521
00:22:21,620 --> 00:22:23,720
easily can be done
in five seconds.

522
00:22:23,720 --> 00:22:27,790
And so they say, an appropriate
amount is 0.12 cents.

523
00:22:27,790 --> 00:22:29,510
You can do the math out, right?

524
00:22:29,510 --> 00:22:31,135
So if it takes five
seconds to do that,

525
00:22:31,135 --> 00:22:32,740
that means you could do what?

526
00:22:32,740 --> 00:22:38,840
Times 2, times 6, so
12 of those per minute.

527
00:22:38,840 --> 00:22:41,000
So 12 times 5 seconds
will give us 60 seconds.

528
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:44,920
So in one minute, you
could do, conceivably,

529
00:22:44,920 --> 00:22:46,390
if it took five
seconds on average,

530
00:22:46,390 --> 00:22:52,480
12 tasks, times 0.012 cents
is 14.4 cents per minute,

531
00:22:52,480 --> 00:22:57,760
times 60 minutes
is $8.64 per hour.

532
00:22:57,760 --> 00:23:00,940
And so that is the
rate that they're

533
00:23:00,940 --> 00:23:03,010
charging for that or the
rate at which they're

534
00:23:03,010 --> 00:23:05,680
scaling that or paying that.

535
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:08,600
So you can pay it at that rate.

536
00:23:08,600 --> 00:23:11,060
And obviously, also, the more
you're willing to pay for it,

537
00:23:11,060 --> 00:23:15,140
the more likely, potentially,
somebody is to take on the task.

538
00:23:15,140 --> 00:23:17,630
But either way, that's what
a low complexity task is.

539
00:23:17,630 --> 00:23:21,235
And you see, they have increased
that as it goes up here.

540
00:23:21,235 --> 00:23:24,080
On the high end, things are
taking about three minutes,

541
00:23:24,080 --> 00:23:27,460
they're paying about
$1.20 per task.

542
00:23:27,460 --> 00:23:30,280
So we'll leave it
at that for now.

543
00:23:30,280 --> 00:23:32,470
Then first off, we need
to declare or check

544
00:23:32,470 --> 00:23:34,907
to specify whether it
contains adult content or not,

545
00:23:34,907 --> 00:23:36,740
because obviously,
that's necessary to know.

546
00:23:36,740 --> 00:23:39,280
I don't even think they'll
allow you to label it.

547
00:23:39,280 --> 00:23:42,310
Or yeah, they'll at
least warn their workers

548
00:23:42,310 --> 00:23:44,360
if there is adult
content in there.

549
00:23:44,360 --> 00:23:45,880
So make sure to
specify that if it's

550
00:23:45,880 --> 00:23:49,337
potentially in there or not.

551
00:23:49,337 --> 00:23:50,920
We need to specify
that you understand

552
00:23:50,920 --> 00:23:53,738
that it's an independent
contractors, so

553
00:23:53,738 --> 00:23:55,280
don't share confidential
information,

554
00:23:55,280 --> 00:23:57,650
personal information, or
protected health information.

555
00:23:57,650 --> 00:24:02,050
You see, it won't even let me
work without unchecking it.

556
00:24:02,050 --> 00:24:05,540
And there's also this step here
of automated data labeling.

557
00:24:05,540 --> 00:24:09,160
So if you think your
tasks are simple enough

558
00:24:09,160 --> 00:24:10,600
or your objects
are simple enough,

559
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:13,720
and you are willing to trust
their machine learning models

560
00:24:13,720 --> 00:24:17,090
to automatically label
them, then you can do that.

561
00:24:17,090 --> 00:24:20,043
I would argue that if
their models can do that,

562
00:24:20,043 --> 00:24:21,960
I wouldn't pay to do
that because there likely

563
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:24,000
exists one publicly
available for free

564
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:25,990
that you could use
to do your labeling.

565
00:24:25,990 --> 00:24:29,140
So it's up to you if you
want to do that or not,

566
00:24:29,140 --> 00:24:32,340
but I'm going to ignore that.

567
00:24:32,340 --> 00:24:37,380
You can also specify the number
of workers per data set object.

568
00:24:37,380 --> 00:24:43,663
So the more people that do
the task, the more reliable

569
00:24:43,663 --> 00:24:44,580
your results could be.

570
00:24:44,580 --> 00:24:45,990
Because basically,
you can vote them

571
00:24:45,990 --> 00:24:47,948
or you can at least see
the confidence in them.

572
00:24:47,948 --> 00:24:49,990
If all three people think
it's the same thing,

573
00:24:49,990 --> 00:24:51,480
then it's going be
100% confident versus

574
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:54,063
if only one person thinks it's
that-- or if each person thinks

575
00:24:54,063 --> 00:24:56,640
it's a different object, then
it might be only 33% confidence

576
00:24:56,640 --> 00:24:58,030
in any one of those.

577
00:24:58,030 --> 00:25:01,902
So that's one way to increase
the reliability of your labels.

578
00:25:01,902 --> 00:25:03,360
Though, recognize,
you're obviously

579
00:25:03,360 --> 00:25:04,318
going to pay multiples.

580
00:25:04,318 --> 00:25:12,630
So if I have 10 images
at 0.12 cents per task,

581
00:25:12,630 --> 00:25:15,930
yeah, that's going to
be 12 cents per task--

582
00:25:15,930 --> 00:25:19,480
or 12 cents, sorry, for
the whole list of images.

583
00:25:19,480 --> 00:25:25,560
And then times 3 will give me
36 cents to label all of these.

584
00:25:25,560 --> 00:25:27,240
So coming down
here then, now, you

585
00:25:27,240 --> 00:25:29,980
can specify the
actual tasks at hand.

586
00:25:29,980 --> 00:25:32,230
So first, you want
to add your labels.

587
00:25:32,230 --> 00:25:38,580
So in this data set, there's
airplanes, cars, boats--

588
00:25:38,580 --> 00:25:44,910
or I'll say, boat, sorry,
singular, helicopter,

589
00:25:44,910 --> 00:25:48,120
or motorcycle.

590
00:25:48,120 --> 00:25:49,690
And here's just a sample.

591
00:25:49,690 --> 00:25:51,630
You can see all 10 of
our images here, though,

592
00:25:51,630 --> 00:25:53,130
arguably, if we had
more, it'll just

593
00:25:53,130 --> 00:25:54,330
give us a subsample of them.

594
00:25:54,330 --> 00:25:56,970
You can also come in here
and provide good example

595
00:25:56,970 --> 00:26:00,250
versus bad examples
for your labeler

596
00:26:00,250 --> 00:26:02,190
so they have
references to go to.

597
00:26:02,190 --> 00:26:05,700
And for that matter, you can
also provide instructions, so

598
00:26:05,700 --> 00:26:06,990
additional instructions.

599
00:26:06,990 --> 00:26:09,032
Because for example, choose
the appropriate label

600
00:26:09,032 --> 00:26:10,470
that best suits the image.

601
00:26:10,470 --> 00:26:14,100
But then I would say
also, maybe if there

602
00:26:14,100 --> 00:26:21,210
are multiple vehicles
in a single image,

603
00:26:21,210 --> 00:26:26,660
please choose the most
prominent vehicle in the image.

604
00:26:30,030 --> 00:26:36,540
So that'll give my labelers
more information about what

605
00:26:36,540 --> 00:26:39,450
is possible in this data set.

606
00:26:39,450 --> 00:26:42,648
Now, finally, you can
click the Create Task.

607
00:26:42,648 --> 00:26:45,190
Now, this is where it's going
to actually start charging you.

608
00:26:45,190 --> 00:26:47,715
So if you click this, be
mindful that it will charge you.

609
00:26:47,715 --> 00:26:50,340
So I'm not going to click it now
because I've already done this

610
00:26:50,340 --> 00:26:52,673
once before, so there's no
reason to duplicate this work

611
00:26:52,673 --> 00:26:55,810
and pay twice for it, even
though it is only 30 cents.

612
00:26:55,810 --> 00:26:57,580
So I'm just going to
click Cancel for now.

613
00:26:57,580 --> 00:27:00,870
But if you had clicked
Create, then it

614
00:27:00,870 --> 00:27:03,300
would come into status
here of In Progress.

615
00:27:03,300 --> 00:27:04,888
So I think it says In Progress.

616
00:27:04,888 --> 00:27:06,930
And it'll tell you how
many labeled objects there

617
00:27:06,930 --> 00:27:07,620
are already.

618
00:27:07,620 --> 00:27:08,890
And it'll take some time.

619
00:27:08,890 --> 00:27:10,952
So it's not an
instantaneous thing.

620
00:27:10,952 --> 00:27:12,660
I think when I did
this, it took probably

621
00:27:12,660 --> 00:27:17,798
like four or five minutes before
all 10 images were labeled.

622
00:27:17,798 --> 00:27:19,840
Though, I'd argue, that's
still pretty impressive

623
00:27:19,840 --> 00:27:23,420
that I was able to reach
out to a global workforce,

624
00:27:23,420 --> 00:27:29,470
get them to accept my task, and
have three people each label

625
00:27:29,470 --> 00:27:31,690
one of the images
or one of our tasks

626
00:27:31,690 --> 00:27:34,490
here, and thereby,
creating this label set.

627
00:27:34,490 --> 00:27:38,120
So it's a really cool
resource in that sense.

628
00:27:38,120 --> 00:27:41,620
But let's click in here and
see what the output looks like.

629
00:27:41,620 --> 00:27:43,790
So you see, there is
my input data set.

630
00:27:43,790 --> 00:27:46,540
There is an output
data set location.

631
00:27:46,540 --> 00:27:49,790
And that is actually
contains all the labels.

632
00:27:49,790 --> 00:27:52,060
And it basically
contains a JSON file

633
00:27:52,060 --> 00:27:53,310
with all the labels in there.

634
00:27:53,310 --> 00:27:56,900
I don't think I've deleted it
yet, so it may still be in here.

635
00:27:56,900 --> 00:28:00,600
If we come down to
Manifests and Output,

636
00:28:00,600 --> 00:28:02,820
we'll just click into this.

637
00:28:02,820 --> 00:28:05,880
Click Open really quick.

638
00:28:05,880 --> 00:28:10,582
And then let me open
this JSON file for you.

639
00:28:10,582 --> 00:28:12,665
So you can see, this is
basically what it returns.

640
00:28:12,665 --> 00:28:14,373
I don't want to open
it in that software,

641
00:28:14,373 --> 00:28:15,660
it's going to take forever.

642
00:28:15,660 --> 00:28:17,790
Here we go.

643
00:28:17,790 --> 00:28:20,760
It just returns this
JSON to you with the name

644
00:28:20,760 --> 00:28:25,046
of the object, the label,
as well as the confidence.

645
00:28:27,630 --> 00:28:29,880
But as you see
here, the confidence

646
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:31,030
isn't always that high.

647
00:28:31,030 --> 00:28:34,770
So for example, some
of these is 72%.

648
00:28:34,770 --> 00:28:38,170
I think one of them,
yeah, down here was 27%.

649
00:28:38,170 --> 00:28:40,910
This was image 0271.

650
00:28:40,910 --> 00:28:43,560
So let's look at this one.

651
00:28:43,560 --> 00:28:45,790
Image 0271.

652
00:28:45,790 --> 00:28:50,010
The predicted label
for this one is--

653
00:28:50,010 --> 00:28:52,750
where are we at here?

654
00:28:52,750 --> 00:28:55,720
Yeah, the predicted
label was Ferry.

655
00:28:55,720 --> 00:28:59,090
So that was the other kind
of boat I added as ferry.

656
00:28:59,090 --> 00:29:02,420
But either way, it predicted
that motorcycle is a ferry.

657
00:29:02,420 --> 00:29:05,300
And then the confidence
here was 0.27.

658
00:29:05,300 --> 00:29:07,310
So not very high
confidence at all,

659
00:29:07,310 --> 00:29:10,180
which is good because it's
very much not a ferry.

660
00:29:10,180 --> 00:29:12,980
But it is the reality
of getting labeled data.

661
00:29:12,980 --> 00:29:16,340
And this is also why, if you're
using this for downstream tasks,

662
00:29:16,340 --> 00:29:19,330
you want to increase the number
of workers that you have,

663
00:29:19,330 --> 00:29:22,490
because you never know what
differences might be there.

664
00:29:22,490 --> 00:29:25,640
I also didn't provide examples
of what each class was.

665
00:29:25,640 --> 00:29:27,910
I just gave them these
images and assumed that they

666
00:29:27,910 --> 00:29:29,438
knew what a ferry was.

667
00:29:29,438 --> 00:29:31,480
There are cultural
differences in this world that

668
00:29:31,480 --> 00:29:34,030
results in language
barriers, potentially,

669
00:29:34,030 --> 00:29:38,420
that maybe result in different
names meaning different things.

670
00:29:38,420 --> 00:29:40,600
And so this is something
you have to be mindful of

671
00:29:40,600 --> 00:29:42,267
and why it'd be very
important if you're

672
00:29:42,267 --> 00:29:45,130
doing this in practice, to
give great examples of what

673
00:29:45,130 --> 00:29:50,017
each possible object
could look like.

674
00:29:50,017 --> 00:29:51,475
But either way,
once you have that,

675
00:29:51,475 --> 00:29:53,450
you at least have
your labeled images

676
00:29:53,450 --> 00:29:57,200
here that now, we could use
for some downstream task

677
00:29:57,200 --> 00:29:59,780
to make our predictions.

678
00:29:59,780 --> 00:30:02,270
Once you have done that,
if you are interested

679
00:30:02,270 --> 00:30:06,410
or if you followed along with
that, feel free to go ahead

680
00:30:06,410 --> 00:30:10,397
and delete any files
that were created

681
00:30:10,397 --> 00:30:12,230
or delete it from the
S3 bucket, because you

682
00:30:12,230 --> 00:30:13,647
will be paying for
anything that's

683
00:30:13,647 --> 00:30:15,560
still stored in your S3 bucket.

684
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:17,550
But if you are just
watching along,

685
00:30:17,550 --> 00:30:20,160
then you should be good to go.

686
00:30:20,160 --> 00:30:22,730
And now, leverage this
tool in the future.

687
00:30:22,730 --> 00:30:25,500
Again, this is something that
is very, very widely used.

688
00:30:25,500 --> 00:30:29,090
I've read countless papers
that have used this as a source

689
00:30:29,090 --> 00:30:30,120
for labeling data.

690
00:30:30,120 --> 00:30:31,730
I've worked at many
companies, where

691
00:30:31,730 --> 00:30:37,320
we are given some massive
data set from our customer.

692
00:30:37,320 --> 00:30:40,260
And they want to know what's in
the images, or better statement,

693
00:30:40,260 --> 00:30:42,575
they want to be able to
predict what might be

694
00:30:42,575 --> 00:30:44,340
in those images in the future.

695
00:30:44,340 --> 00:30:47,130
So for example, in one
of my previous jobs,

696
00:30:47,130 --> 00:30:49,520
I was working with a lot
of satellite imagery.

697
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:52,050
And we had countless images.

698
00:30:52,050 --> 00:30:55,060
I mean, you can imagine,
each of these satellites

699
00:30:55,060 --> 00:30:58,640
is circling the world
every 90 minutes.

700
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:01,280
So we're just getting
unbelievable amounts of data.

701
00:31:01,280 --> 00:31:03,760
And if I'm trying to identify
cars, and boats, and planes

702
00:31:03,760 --> 00:31:06,730
in these images, I
can't physically even

703
00:31:06,730 --> 00:31:10,880
hire enough people to do this
task on an ongoing basis.

704
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:12,610
But I can leverage
Mechanical Turk

705
00:31:12,610 --> 00:31:15,380
or similar labeling
services to do that.

706
00:31:15,380 --> 00:31:18,880
So that's the idea behind this.

707
00:31:18,880 --> 00:31:20,718
That's the usefulness of this.

708
00:31:20,718 --> 00:31:23,260
And it's such a critical part
of the Machine Learning process

709
00:31:23,260 --> 00:31:25,700
that I couldn't leave
it out for this.

710
00:31:25,700 --> 00:31:27,560
So we'll leave that here now.

711
00:31:27,560 --> 00:31:30,310
In the next class, we'll
get to the step beyond this.

712
00:31:30,310 --> 00:31:32,520
Once we have our data, once
we have our label data,

713
00:31:32,520 --> 00:31:35,020
how do we go about actually
creating Machine Learning models

714
00:31:35,020 --> 00:31:36,190
in the cloud?

715
00:31:36,190 --> 00:31:36,790
OK.

716
00:31:36,790 --> 00:31:37,728
Thanks for watching.

717
00:31:37,728 --> 00:31:39,020
And I'll talk to you next time.

718
00:31:39,020 --> 00:31:40,570
Bye.